  "doc_id": "8459",
  "text": "Toxoplasma gondii (T. gondii) is a protozoan parasite that commonly infects humans and animals [CITATION_1] . Humans are generally infected by ingesting oocysts released in cat feces or by consuming undercooked meat containing tissue cysts. Following ingestion, bradyzoites and sporozoites released from cysts and oocysts invade intestinal cells and convert to tachyzoites [CITATION_2] , which when disseminated via blood or the lymphatic system to remote organs induce acute or chronic inflammatory responses. Furthermore, during the chronic stage, the brain is the most commonly affected site [CITATION_3] . T. gondii is a serious pathogen that can invade vital organs, but usually the infection is mild and asymptomatic in immunocompetent hosts. Possible clinical manifestations include lymphadenopathy, myocarditis, hepatitis, sepsis syndrome, retinochoroiditis, and encephalitis [CITATION_4] . However, normally the infection becomes chronic, remains latent in the brain, and elicits life-long immunity against toxoplasmosis [CITATION_5] .",
